{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_babelfish_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280656902/1921031901/0660.xml":{"full_text":"M'\nBUSINESS SECTION r?\ngbmrng giaf Classified Ads.\nPart Two. WASHINGTON, D.~C., SATURDAY, MARCH 19, 1921 12 Page?~\nBUYING NECESSARY\nTO BRINE STABILITY\n\nSecretary Mellon Calls Producing\nand Selling, Even to\nGermany, Vital Need.\nOnly by return of the public to\nhe buying market will conditions be\nstabilized, according to those who\nhave been watching conditions in the\nbnsiness field for months. The principal\nmatter to be considered now is\nto move product^? and by moving\nthem the manufacturer will be able\nto collect his money, and in turn\nwill be able to put all of his employes\nagain to work and start the wheels\nof Industry moving.\nSecretary Mellon of the Treasury\nDepartment has pointed out that the\nprime consideration in the country\ntoday Is to get products on the market\nand sell them. Nothing short of this\nwill help the return of the prosperity\nto this country. So important did\nthe new Secretary of Treasury consider\nthis that he thinks that prod?\nuets should be sent to Germany. The\nWar Finance Corporation has authorized\na loan to cotton merchants for\na supply of cotton, part of which\ngoes to the country with which the\nITnited States is technically at war.\nWhen these products are moved out\nof the warehouses and money pro\nvioeu iwr iiicir mw yciubh v\nIn the channels of commerce through\nthe governmental aid of the finance\ncorporation, then prosperity again\nwill begin to show up in the country.\nContinuous Ctrele.\nProsperity, it was pointed out. Is\nJust a continuous circle of one buying\nfrom the other, and the extent to\nwhich this buying takes place marks\nthe depth and height of prosperity.\nFood, shelter, clothing, comforts, etc.,\nmust .be bought from the manufacturers.\nretailers, and the like, so they, in\nturn, can buy time, skill, experience\nand materials.\nWaiting for prices to come down\nhurts every one down the line. All are\naffected to the extent that buying is\nstopped. The carrying of the so-called\nbuyers' strike to an extreme Is the\ngerm which has brought the country\nto the run-down commercial condition\nin which it now finds itself, according\nto those in close touch with\nthe situation.\nAll Most Poll Together.\n\"Based on his present costs, which\nInclude the money you are earning,\nthe manufacturer, jobber and retailer\nhas reduced his prices as far as he\nthinks he can?and still continue to\nemploy you and remain in business\nhimself,\" says the Youngstown Daily\nVindicator, commenting on the situation.\n\"If we push him farther down, it\ncatches us in the long run,\" it further\nsays. \"By buying wisely and prudently\nnow. we can start the wheels\nof prosperity?and stabilize the conditions\nunder which we all must live.\n\"Each of us can assure his own personal\nwelfare and income, only by assuring.\nfirst, the welfare and income\nof all.\" r\nmmUaj^u^^^M i f -d\nf O a\nYou Rememb\nThe children's rainy day 1\nthe-way place, with odd nook\nand boxes full of wonders to\nA great place to keep away fi\n\"Be quiet!\"?and absolutely 1\nboy to read \"The Last of the 1\ni It ia just such things as this\n\"a place to live\" and \"home.\"\nEach of the homes on Ingra\nattic. Why, there is space for ti\nbeing to provide storage space f\nthe closets are not jammed and th\nV>sa Kotfom of th^ trunk\n6 on the North SideIngraham\nStreet i\nThere are five bedrooms and\nand the living rooms are full dept\npictured above) have four bedr<\nfortable living rooms; and an exl\nfirst floor, this \"clubroom\" beir\nrecent years in home building.\nThere are large front and r<\nished third floor (space for twi\nracks to keep shoes off the flooi\nin short, every possible refineme\nAll detached, on large lotshouses\nin a row I\nDO NOT POSTPON\nTake Fourteenth Street\nAve.\" (best service in VVashii\nor drive out Sixteenth Stree\nwest, then one square to Inj\nSHANNON\n713 14th\nI\nAGGREGATE OF $425,000\nIN WEEK'S REALTY DEALS\nLocal Firm's Transactions Embrace\nthe Transfer of Four Apart\nmeni IIUUSCO 1U buncato\nRealty transactions In which four\napartment buildings in the northwest I\nsection changed owners, with an aggregate\nconsideration of about $425.000\ninvolved, were consummated this\nweek through the office of Hedges\nMiddleton, Inc.\nThe largest deal resulted In the\ntransfer of the two practically new j\napartment houses, 2100 and 2106 N!\nstreet northwest, by Charles D. Weldenhamer\nto Anna It. Hurley in exchange\nfor the Ingleside apartment\nhouse. Lamont street, just east of\nMount Pleasant street northwest. The\nIngleside was given in part payment.\nThe second transaction was the acquisition\nby Mr. Weidenhamer of a\nnew apartment building in course of\ncompletion by Harry Wardman. at the\ncorner of 27th street and Cathedral\navenue northwest. The consideration\nis said to have been in the neighborhood\nof $125,000.\nThe two N street apartment houses\nare four-story structures, containing\na -tot\"! of forty-four housekeeping\napartments of from two rooms and\nbath to four rooms and bath. each.\nThe buildings are entirely modern\nand centain a number of innovations\nunusual to this type of abode.\nThe Ingleside contains twenty-one\napartments of from one to five rooms\neach and is equipped with every modern\nconvenience. Mr. Hurley was\nrepresented by Moore Hill. Inc.\nThe new Wardman building comI\nprises sixteen apartments of three\nI and four rooms each. The construcjtion\nis fireproof and modern. Mr.\nWeidenhamer will hold the building\nfor investment purposes, it is underj\nstood.\nOPENS REALTY OFFICE.\nF. M. Johnson Active in Beal Estate\nfor Many Tears.\nF. M. Johnson, who has been actively\nengaged In the building trade\nIn Washington for several years, has\nopened real estate brokerage offices\nat 1110 Connecticut avenue, where he\nwill conduct a sales, rents, loans and\ninsurance business in connection with\nI construction work.\nS. H. Lowther. who has-been con|\nnected with Mr. Johnson for the past\ntwo years as his building superintendent,\nwill have charge of the ofJ\nflee. Mr. Lowther is an experienced\nbuilder and real estate salesman.\nAfter looking the situation over in\nmany of the larger cities of the United\nStates and Canada, he decided to\nlocate, permanently in Washington\nHe is very enthusiastic over the business\noutlook here and expects to organize\na strong sales force.\nThe F. M. Johnson Realty Company.\nas the new Arm will be known,\nhave well equipped offices At their\nnew location.\nBUSINESS PBOPEBTY SOLD.\nSale of the business property at\n1206 G street northwest to Mrs. Sophie\nR. Harris was announced today by\nShannon Luchs. The building formerly\nwas owned by Joseph Sperling.\nIt is understood that Mrs. Harris will\nremove her F street shop to the new\nlocation.\ner the Attic? 1\nm HI\nresort?a comiortaDie, out-ots\nand corners, and old trunks\nthe youngster's curious mind,\nom the grown folks' constant\nthe only place on earth for a\nVIohicans.\"\nthat make the difference between\n:ham St. at Nth has a great, big\nwo more rooms?part of the idea\nor all things out of use, so that\ne thing you want is not inevitably\n-6 on the South Side\nit 14th Northwest\nthree baths in the corner homes,\nh. The other homes (one of them\n>om and two baths; large, com:ra\nroom (the \"clubroom\") on the\nig the greatest step forward in\ntar porches; linen closets; unfin3\nmore rooms); all closets with\nr; hot-water heat and electricity;\nnt. i\n1\n-yet tney sell tor less than new\nE BEYOND TODAY j\n:ar marked \"14th and Colorado\nigton) to corner of Ingraham,\nit to Colorado Avenue NorthGraham\nStreet.\nLUCHS\nrx *.r ti;\nPERMITS TO BUILD\nTOUT!\nBig Jump Shown in Homes\nPlanned for District During\nPast Week.\nMore than J100.000 in home construction\npermits were issued this\nweek to local builders by the District\nbuilding: inspector. The number of\npermits granted during: the week exrvrevieus\nrecords for several\nweeks preceding:.\nII. R. Howenstein was granted permission\nto begin the erection of seven\nhomes. 3600 to 3612 Park place northwest,\nfacing Soldiers' Home Park.\nThe cost of the operation was given\nas $30,000.\nMiddaugh Shannon, Incorporated,\nwill build four houses at 1002 to 1008\nShepherd street northwest at a cost\nof $24,000.\nSamuel Shapiro tiled plans for a\n$30,000 residence at 4834 *16th street\nnorthwest.\nOther Home Projects.\nSeveral other home projects were\nrecorded. The list of permits follows:\nC. H. Wlllingham. to repair 121 10th\nstreet southeast: cost. $100.\nG. F. C. Smillie, to repair 717 12th\nstreet; cost, $300.\nTony Albate, to repair 2307 Pennsylvania\navenue southeast; cost, $200.\nMollie Swartz, to build store 2406\nConnecticut avenue; cost, $6,500.\nW. H. Lofgren, to repair 3416 Oliver\nstreet; cost, $200.\nSam Stoller, to repair 1032 D street\nnortheast; cost, $600.\nW. C. Murphy, to build dwelling 1227\nMassachusetts avenue southeast; cost,\n$8,000.\nB. M. Conradis. to erect garage rear\n221 Rhode Island avenue; cost, $1,200.\nH. W. Noel, to erect garage rear 616\n6th street southeast; cost, $200.\nJ. W. Payne, to erect garage rear 727\nMorton street; cost, 200.\nA. C. Nothstine, to erect garage rear\n1216 Gallatin street; cost. $400.\nJ. W. Lovegrove, to erect garage 1345\nMeridian place: cost, $280.\nC. J. Hanback, to build frame\ndwellings, 516-518 65th street northeast;\ncost. $1,000.\nP. M. Anderson, to erect garage\nrear znz a sireei; turn, ii#?.\nM. Moskowita, to repair 2112 14th\nstreet: cost, $3,000.\nWilliam Murphy, to build 719-721 P\nstreet northeast: cost, $5,000.\nJ. A. Specht, to repair rear 41 Q\nstreet northeast; cost, $250.\nAaron H. Frear, to erect garage\nrear 223 8th street southeast; cost,\n$175.\nR. B. Speaker, to erect garage 3011\n20th street northeast; cost, $600.\nJ. 8. Owens, to erect garage rear\n510 G street southeast; cost, $345.\nG. E. Rothrock, to repair 174