n ascertaining the c\nvalue of city lots and the use to which t\nthey can be put, because the ultimate t\nvalue of your lot is the revenue it will\nproduce when built on with the proper i\nkind of improvements. There is no j\nother criterion by which you can be t\nguided.\nMentions Heat Regulations. c\n\"I want to say Just a word on the\nsubject of rent regulations. Capital r\nis a very delicate thing with which j\nto tamper. It takes some courage\nunder present conditions for a man\nto build, and if laws are passed which J\nare going to restrict the use of build-\ning, you will find that they will not f\nbe built. A bill introduced in the last\nCongress passed the Senate and\no htnr TP U C\nnil caicucu lU wcvwiuc a. mrr? it. ib j\nhad it would almost have made\napartment houses impossible of operation.\nIt would have made it impossible\nto eject an undesirable\ntenent. When an occupant of an\napartment house becomes objection-\nable, you must get rid of him for the i\ngood of the many?tor the good of j\nthe respectable people who are living\nin the same building. I hope this bill\nwill not be revived at the next\nsession.\n\"Some tenants have so little regard\nfor the comfort of the neighbors as S\nto go out of the way to annoy them. 1\niome for\nS|&P?y\nRJR\nTypio\nher 2.\ni\n\n$100.. .$13,900.00\n2,500.00\n3.858.68\n$13,358.68\n541.32\n7,500.00\nse $8,041.32\nVDLO/?D or some\ntE.Wal\nOriginators of the P<\ntive Plan of Owners!\nith Street\nrecall soma years aco the occupan\n>f two apartments, one over the othe\ntot at loR-perheads, One claimed th,\nhe other moved his furniture bat\nind forth over his apartment to ket\nlim awake. About two days later tl\nither came in.\nflock Cannes Eviction.\n\"He mid that the man underneat\nnanatred to find out the location c\nhe room In which the first Rentlems\nlad his bed. Then he attached J\ndarm clock to the ceilinp above iKht\nunder the bed. the alarm heir\n;et so as to sound every half hot\nhroutthout the niKht. When yt\nome in contact with people like th;\nou have to get rid of them.\"\n\"In the City the vacant lot is 01\nhat should be purchased with a etc;\nleal of care. Sometimes you find\ntood value, but as a rule the sma\nrity lot is overvalued. Few peop\n>uild 8itiEle houses. The profltab\nhinE to do is to build a row i\n;ouses, which can be constructed mui\nnore cheaply. An apartment hou;\ns the cheapest form of housiti\nknown.\"\nJOINS REAL ESTATE FIRM\nformer Assistant District Attorne\nMade Vice President of Company\nJames P. Sohlck, who recently ri\n;igned as assistant United States dii\nrict attorney, has joined the real e;\nate firm of John W. Thompson C\nA vice president and general mar\niger.\nMr. Schick is experienced !.n the re;\nstate field, having been engaged 1\n>usiness some years ago with Moo;\n1: Hill, and before that with the Di;\nrict and Washington Title Insuran*\nsompanies. He is a lawyer by pri\nession and for a number of yeai\ntracticed this pursuit.\nMr. Schick will have supervision i\nhe sales negotiations and of the get\n;ral business of the Thompson Con\n>any.\nWANTED?HOME GARDENS.\nrrom the Chieego Nrwi.\nWhat the newly organized Nation\nHome Garden Association may suseed\nin accomplishing when it leavi\nhe office and the armchair for the a\nual struggle with the prairie sc\n8. or course, not yet Known, dui u\niroposal to found 10,000 gardens\nhis poorly vegetated town Is wort!\n>f serious consideration.\nNot only would 10,000 gardens fu\nilsh many a flourishing onion ar\nlead of lettuce to meet Chicago's d<\nnand for vitamins and minerals, bi\nhey would give much needed mor\nliscipline. A man who can cultiva\nl hill of beans according to the Ju\naws of nature is not likely to 1\nLfflicted with the speed hysterias\nither disciplin&ry diseases prevalei\nn the streets.\nThere are unquestionable moral ai\nrntages in a garden patch fitted\nioothe the phrenetic activities of tl\n:ity. The calm dignity of the cabhaf\nvaxing to maturity and the deliber;\nion of the ripening squash might f\nar to improve the morale of our u\nian population.\nAnd think what a well cultivati\ngarden does to a grocery bill!\nMore than one-quarter of all Uniti\nStates lumber exports are sent\nL.atin American markets.\nniiiiiiiiiiii ffliiiiiiiiiiiiiiii\nyour o\nife'\n1\nad Interior of a Walker Co-op\nNumbe\nPurchase, price\nof apartment, $4,600.00\nCash payment. 1,500.00\nTotal monthly\npayment, expenses,\nprincipal\nand interest\n51.70\nPresent rental, 70.00\nTotal rental 139 months at\nCash payment $1,5\nTotal payment 139\nmonths at $51.70 7.1\nTotal\nSavings in caslr,\nValue of apartment\nActual Gain by Purchase\njne's tenant?\nker\njrfected Co-Operalip\nin Washington\nSouth\nilllllilM\n1 BUILDING SUPPLY\nI SHORTAGE POSSIBLE\n01\nin i\nin\nIncreased Activity in Construction\nWork Cited as\nLikely Cause.\nit\na Reports indicate a continuance of\nv preparations for extensive building\nactivities and point to a propitious\nat construction season, according to 8.\n\"b w. Straus, the New York banker.\n\"Active conditions are likely to de*\nvelop a serious shortage in supplies,\"\nhe declares. \"The general funda\nmental conditions cannot be said to\nbe conducive to lower building prices;\nin fact, the activities which now apy\npear to be getting under way may\nbo expected in the natural course of\nevents to strengthen prices.\nLower Labor oats.\n\"In some localities there have been\nrecessions in labor costs due to uno.\nemployment and general business Ucpres.si\non, but it would not be prudent\nto withhold building plans on\nthe assumption of further prospecal\ntive general recessions in labor.\nln \"Tile hopeful aspect of the building\nsituation is to be taken as a forero\nrunner of general business revival,\ns- Pronounced building activities will\nhasten economic and social atabilixalion.\nThe agitation and unrest which has\nexisted in the Industry will, ln\nthe long run, prove beneficial. Peopie\nare continually demanding better\nhomes and higher standards of llving.\nThe development of our great\nAmerican cities, the upbuilding of the\nnation and the general progress of\ncivilization have been due primarily\nto the restless aspirations of humanity\nfor better living standards. Tha\nsocial unrest in the world today la\nal a further manifestation of these irac_\npulses, and stabilized conditions will\nbe brought about by directing these\nss forces along constructive lines. Succ\ncess is discontent expressed in terms\n)d accomplishment.\nie Solution for t'nrrst.\nIn \"These facts are to be borne iB\niv mind in connection with every phase\nof the present situation. Such activities\nas home-building and homer\"\nownership will- prove rightful enid\ndeavors through which unrest may\nAnd constructive solution.\n\"The present prospects of active\nresidential construction during the\na' ensuing spring and summer, therefore,\nhave a deeper significance thaa\n~5 appears on the surtace. iney repie'\nsent a forward movement toward bet*\nter social conditions; they will alle?\n11 viate much of the unrest which bad\nexisted since the end of the war, will\nj give lmpei t? to general business, will\n0 make possible more general prac*\n'e tlces of thrift and remove many ol\nthe ills now due to unemployment.\"\nto\nr- Lumber waste prevention and utll?\nization will be studied by a special\n5d bureau of the National Lumber Manu*\nfacturers' Association.\npd Wages in building trades in Londos\nto have not decreased in a period of 708\nyears, except for brief periods.\n>/c/^ qg-e\nerative Apartment j\nrr 3.\nI\nI! ss\ni\n0.... $9,730.00\n00.00\n86.30 J g\ncs f&A\n$1,043.70 H\n4.600.00 H\n$5,643.70 J\n\nCO., J\nern Building 1\nft\nmr-^L t -.v..''' .ImBm","height":"29504","width":"22940"}}
